A Republican strategy to hinder Obama’s re-election
Republican leaders justified their policy of the need to fight electoral fraud.
Now, the Brennan Center considers the latter a myth and claims that electoral fraud is less prevalent in the United States than the number of people dying from lightning strikes.
In fact, Republican lawyers have found no more than 300 cases of voter fraud in the United States in ten years.
One thing is certain: those new provisions will negatively affect the participation rate.
In that sense, these measures will partly undermine the American democratic system.
Contrary to what happens in Canada, American states are responsible for organizing the federal elections in the United States.
And along the same lines, a majority of American governments enacted, starting in 2009, new laws that hindered the registration or voting process.
This phenomenon has spread after the November 2010 election, which saw the increase of 675 new Republican representatives in 26 states.
Accordingly, 180 bills were introduced during 2011 that restricted the exercise of the right to vote in 41 states.
The new election laws require voters to file an identity card with a photograph, in addition to a proof of American citizenship.
Moreover, these laws reduce early voting periods, invalidate the right to register as a voter on the day of scrutiny, and withdraw their right to vote to citizens with criminal records.
Before the 2006 election, no American state demanded that voters present a photo ID.
The State of Indiana was the first to demand it.
The U.S. Supreme Court confirmed the constitutionality of Indiana law in 2008.
Republican authorities were quick to extend that practice to other states.
In recent years, the authorities have supported bills in 34 states to force voters to file a photo ID.
It is important to note that, contrary to what happens in Quebec, American citizens do not have a universal identity card, such as the Social Security card.
In fact, 11% of American citizens, that is, 21 million people of voting age, do not have any photo IDs issued by a government agency in their state.
On the other hand, five million new voters in 2012 lack an identity document with such characteristics.
But often obtaining the required identity document costs more than a hundred dollars.
The new restrictions disproportionately affect young people, minorities and people with low incomes.
In fact, 25% of African-Americans, 15% of people who earn less than 35,000 dollars a year, 18% of citizens over 65 and 20% of voters between the ages of 18 and 29 do not have a photo ID.
And there's even more.
In many states students, voters who vote most for Democratic candidates, cannot use the photo ID issued by their institution.
On the other hand, those same states authorize members of fishing or hunting clubs who usually vote for Republican parties to use the documents issued by such clubs.
Before 2004 no state required citizenship testing to vote.
Arizona was the first state to file this requirement.
Since 2011, a dozen states have adopted laws requiring voters to prove they are American citizens.
Those measures clearly seek to limit the Hispanic vote.
It seems that two out of every three Hispanic voters support the Democratic party.
On the other hand, Republican lawmakers supported in 2011 certain laws that abolished the registration of voters on the same day of scrutiny in eight states.
In addition, they limited the right of individuals and groups to create a service to voters who would like to register.
These restrictions have consequences.
For example, in the 2004 general election, voter registration campaigns contributed to the registration of around 10 million citizens.
The measures taken since 2009 resulted in the registration rate of new voters falling in 2010 compared to 2006.
In addition, Republican lawmakers adopted laws in five other states that favored the reduction of the voting period in advance.
For example, in the 2008 elections in Florida, 33 percent of voters who voted in advance were African-American, while the latter accounted for 13 percent of the state’s voters.
In the case of Hispanics, the same thing happened.
These represent no more than 11% of voters, which is equivalent to 24% of citizens who vote in advance.
However, whites, who represent 76% of the electorate, account for only 46% of citizens who vote in advance.
Of course, Democratic lawmakers and their supporters have fervently opposed the adoption of laws that restrict voter registration.
Democratic governors have blocked several bills.
The U.S. Attorney’s Office intervened to suspend the most controversial laws.
It was partly possible to limit the damage.
For example, only 16 out of 34 states adopted the law requiring the filing of a photo ID.
However, it is undeniable that the new rules adopted will complicate the exercise of the right to vote in 2012.
Democratic critics denounce the partisan character of the laws that have been voted on, since it is clear that they are intended to influence the results of 2012 in the key states.
A 2011 Brennan Center report shows that the states that have adopted such laws represent 171 of the 270 votes needed in the electoral college to win the presidency.
It is too early to state with certainty whether these legislative changes at the electoral system scale will have a significant impact on the results of the 2012 presidential election.
One thing is certain: those new provisions will negatively affect the participation rate.
In this regard, the measures will partly undermine the American democratic system.
