The Higgs boson in detail
The announcement of the likely discovery of the Higgs boson generated a huge commotion last summer, and rightly so.
It is believed, in fact, that this boson is partaker of the mechanism responsible for the mass of everything that exists in the universe, nothing more and nothing less.
What’s more, it’s about the particle whose existence predicted the standard model: our better or less “bad” explanation of the nature and behavior of matter, which has not yet been empirically observed.
But for physicists it is not entirely clear that it is Higgs.
We know without a doubt that there is a new particle and that it is very similar to the Higgs boson predicted by the standard model.
In addition, new data revealed this week at a major physics congress held in Kyoto seem to confirm that it is, although there is still more data to be completely safe.
Anyway, we assume that it is Higgs, since the chances of being wrong seem few. We'll see what it's about.
There is, in this great world, a generalized and inescapable law that implies that two things cannot be found in the same place at the same time.
There is no way to violate that rule and don’t try too hard, because it will end up hurting itself.
Although particle physics is a very complex world, it has been shown that there is also a law of these characteristics in it: the principle of exclusion of Pauli, which stipulates that two particles cannot occupy the same space at the same time if they are in the same "quantum state"; a "state" consisting, roughly, of some of its characteristics.
Physicists classify particles into two categories.
On the one hand we meet the good citizens called fermions, who obey the principle of Pauli wisely.
And on the other are the bosons, a dirty panda of anarchists who have no respect for anything, or at least not for this principle, which means that they can be found in the same place and at the same time.
According to the website The Particle Adventure of Berkeley Laboratories that, by the way, is extraordinary, bosons are divided into two groups: the mesons, which we will not talk about here, and the "particles of force", for which the great forces of nature propagate and with which the Higgs boson would be somehow related.
These bosons, it might be underlined here, they are not the exotic bugs we could believe.
In fact, if you manage to read this chronicle, it is thanks to an extraordinarily banal boson: the photon or the "particle of light" that acts as a "messenger" of the electromagnetic force.
Indeed, when a particle with an electric charge accelerates or changes direction, it "disorders" the electromagnetic field in that precise environment; a little like when we throw a stone into a pond.
In this "disorder" an electromagnetic wave (from light, from infrared, from ultraviolets, etc.) is born, and this wave is nothing but a photon; that is, one of the "force-bearing" bosons.
More stable field
The same thing happens with the Higgs boson, with the difference that it is another field, the Higgs field, which needs to be "disordered" for this boson to appear.
Now, the Higgs field is much more stable than the electromagnetic field. To activate it, it is necessary to reach extremely high energies, a little as if it were an icy pond in which only a thick rock could slide down the surface.
That is why it takes a huge particle accelerator like CERN (the large hadron collider is a 27 km-circumference ring!) to reach such energy levels.
The analogy with the electromagnetic field is a new tool that explains the relationship between Higgs and mass.
In fact, not all particles or all materials interact with the electromagnetic field.
Some, like magnets, do, but others don’t: a piece of paper, for example, will never hold itself attached to a refrigerator door.
And in the same way, not all particles interact with the Higgs field: those that do have a mass, while the rest (like the photon, by the way), do not have it.
Now, what "can they" bring all of those investigations? asks Mrs. Plamondon.
For science, this serves to verify the validity of the standard model (MS), and also allows physicists to scrutinize the differences between observations and MS predictions.
For their part, many fervently want them to be found, because the slightest difference could open a door to a "new physics" that covers certain holes of the model.
This, it must be said, still has enormous deficiencies, as it does not propose any explanation regarding gravity (ups!) or dark matter, which makes up about 80% of the matter of the Universe (another ups!).
But we have not found such differences in CERN so far.
Repercussions
The repercussions of such research in our day to day lives are difficult to predict, but we do not believe that we are wrong to say that it will have none.
To see: in the early 60’s, the pioneers of the laser in the laboratories did not suspect at all the revolution that their work would provoke.
They swayed scientific applications, but nothing more.
In fact, as physicist Willard Boyle, who worked in Bell laboratories, where the laser was invented in 1960, and who made the first continuous laser (the first was pulsed) in 1962, at first the laser was rather considered a "lab apparatus".
Imagine...
And in addition, the applications can also come from all the instrumentation surrounding the research.
For example, Willard Boyle himself developed a light picker in 1969 in the course of his optics research.
Although it was not at all his original intention, this catcher now serves as an "eye" for all the digital devices in the world, which earned him the Nobel Prize in physics in 2009.
