Bitcoin differs from other systems with types of virtual currencies such as “credits”, used to advance in a video game and that can be earned by playing or can be bought (and even sometimes redeemed).
Facebook also developed this type of system.
But in every exchange a central authority controls and treats the changes.
With bitcoin, all network nodes are both book depositors, verifiers, currency issuers and buyers and sellers.
How does that network work?
Each transaction between two users is actually made between two e-mail addresses.
A user can choose a different address for each payment, thus guaranteeing anonymity.
A set of information linked to this transaction is electronically signed through a dual-key encryption system.
The network can thus verify the authenticity of the transaction.
Thanks to the content of the file, it is also possible to ensure that bitcoin changes are in the public account book, which is disseminated throughout the network.
The key milestone is to write that new transaction in that book.
This is the resolution of a mathematical challenge launched to the computers and the winner, a kind of provisional central banker, will have the privilege of adding that complementary line.
It is a phase of file chopping, that is, transformation of a large file into a shorter and unique numerical footprint.
Computers "take" the new transaction and add a number before "chopping" the set.
The goal is to find the number that offers a particular footprint (zero at the beginning).
Once that number is found, the other nodes easily verify that it is the good one.
The transaction is then indestructibly linked to the chain of sets of the other transactions; any modification would change the footprint.
If, to commit a fraud, a user would want to pay twice with the same money very quickly (in less than ten minutes), the network would only accept as valid one of the two transactions; the other would be orphaned, since both have different footprints.
The computer that solves the challenge takes 50 bitcoins.
To avoid inflation, that reward is divided into two regularly, with probability before the end of 2012.
The number of bitcoins in circulation is therefore limited to 21 million, but they are divisible to the 100th, which leaves a wide margin.
The difficulty of this challenge is also revealed in each increase in the computing power.
The life of the network already has its ups and downs.
Websites that offer services for Bitcoin have been attacked and bitcoins have been stolen in deposit.
“The failure used does not affect the same protocol,” said Pierre Noizat, who has just launched Paymium, a real currency payment company that uses the Bitcoin network.
The ECB also takes into account the possibilities of money laundering thanks to this anonymous service.
But cash has the same defect.
Weight actors like Wikipedia reject payments of this type.
Others, like the Wordpress platform, accept them.
Recently, Adi Shamir and Dorit Ron of the Weizmann Institute in Israel analyzed the ledger and showed that about 80% of bitcoins do not circulate.
In November the "giant sales" were launched.
“30,000 dollars were changed,” rejoices Jon Holmquist, who works for Coinabul, which turns bitcoins into gold.
Pierre Noizat, author of a pedagogical book on that currency, believes quite a bit in the potential of this technology in addition to the transaction network.
Its system, Paytunia, equals a credit card (in real currency) or a contactless mobile payment, but it uses Bitcoin to validate transactions, which come out cheaper.
The bearer also manages his identity and can therefore remain anonymous.
The system is easy to launch in merchants, who do not have to install new terminals or software.
It is enough for them to supply an address that a phone can "photograph and recognize", says Pierre Noizat, who claims to have thousands of users.
There is a general movement of revision of hierarchical systems by more horizontal systems.
“It will take a while for Bitcoin to prevail, but in 2013 there could be a change,” he predicts.
On the other hand, in its report the ECB plans to re-evaluate the various risks, today considered high, if this currency is successful.
