Traveling on any type of public transport costs 6 shéquels and for this price you can travel by transhipping for 1.5 hours.
In Israel, according to Jewish tradition, the Sabbath is celebrated on Saturdays.
From Friday night until Saturday sunset, markets and shops close and public transport interrupts their work.
But on Sunday morning a new workweek begins.
In many cafes, restaurants and hotels only kosher food is served, which excludes pork, seafood, flakeless fish and dishes in which milk and meat are combined.
There is offered a wide selection of dishes based on beef and lamb, soups and desserts prepared with coconut milk, the traditional Hebrew cream called hummus, a great variety of sauces, the falafel, which are balls of ground chickpea, fruits and vegetables.
In the streets of Israeli cities you don’t see stray dogs.
