Each year, 13 million immigrant workers arrive in Moscow, St. Petersburg and other cities in Russia.
They are mostly citizens of Central Asian countries: Uzbekistan, Tajikistan and Turkmenistan.
Their only goal is to earn money to help their families who have stayed home.
From December 1 a law enters into force, according to which each working immigrant must take an exam to check their knowledge of the Russian language.
For now, this rule applies only to those who intend to work in the service delivery sector, community service institutions, domestic services and retail.
However, over time, as promised in the Federal Immigration Service, exams will be made mandatory for all immigrants.
In addition, it will not be enough to take the language exam, but also that of Russian history and the fundamentals of the legislation.
Knowledge of the language should even be confirmed to receive and renew the work permit.
Exceptions are citizens of countries where Russian is the official language.
People who managed to obtain their education certificates and diplomas before the dissolution of the Soviet Union in 1991 will not be subject to this law.
Utility, fatality and defence of rights
The network of examination centers will operate under the Swiss Language Institute, the People’s Friendship University, Moscow State University, St. Petersburg State University and other Russian higher education institutions.
Immigrants will be able to take the tests in all cities, right now in Russia more than 160 such centers are open.
