Only an organized selection system will solve the problem of immigrant workers in 90% of cases.
The problems are the immigrants without profession, education, those who do not know the language or pass the medical control.
Without understanding the language, Sebelev says, the future immigrant will be condemned to find unscrupulous people who, under the pretext of helping, put a "paid trip" to a creepy, narrow covacha, where he and dozens of others like him are consumed for months without food or documents, working 12 to 14 hours a day.
We received countless complaints from our immigrants.
“In their homeland they promise them one thing, but when they arrive they are deceived, they are deprived of their passports, they are not paid the promised salaries,” confirms the Chief of the Labor Immigration Directorate of the Immigration Service of Tajikistan, Tolib Sharipov.
Don't be upset, little boss!
However, in the meantime many citizens of the Central Asian republics who wish to work in Russia recognize that not only do they not know the language of the country they intend to go to, but also in their own language they write with difficulty.
Of course, this is not so much their fault but their own misfortune: there are few Turkmens, Uzbeks, Tajiks who can afford to receive normal primary education.
This is because their families even have nothing to feed the children, not to mention dressing them, wearing them and buying them what is necessary for the school.
When they reach adolescence, these kids venture to work at the first opportunity.
It is difficult, if you do not know the language, they recognize.
"You feel humiliated and inferior."
However, with regard to the language law, rights defenders point out an important point.
The exams will be conducted only for those immigrants whose status is legal.
If they do not have that status, there will be no examination and, consequently, no official work.
Meanwhile, most immigrant workers continue to live in Russia illegally.
"Welcome or forbidden the passage to strangers"
Many visitors claim that receiving official status in our country is not so easy.
The cause lies in the bureaucratic obstacles and difficulties of the language itself.
In addition, legalization costs money: from twelve thousand to sixteen thousand rubles.
However, a false inscription can be made quickly and for only a thousand five hundred rubles.
Employees of the Russian police know that we usually carry false documents, are not registered and extortion cases appear.
"We are asked for a hundred or two hundred rubles for cigarettes or tea," Tajikistan citizen Umed Hushkadamov told reporters.
"Come on, don't be stingy, buy a painting"
On the first day of the entry into force of the language law, it was revealed that not only immigrant registration documents can be false.
Several "false" certificates of language knowledge have already been seized by Federal Immigration Service officials.
Counterfeit documents had been printed on standard color printers.
Of course, they came into the hands of the new owners not as a gift: each immigrant, wanting to facilitate the task of passing the tests, paid for the document seven thousand rubles.
This is two and a half times more expensive than the official examination procedure, which will cost the immigrant worker three thousand rubles.
The main task for the near future is to protect the system against corruption so that “diplomas” cannot be bought, government officials and rights defenders converge.
So far, the authorities can promise immigrant workers who would not have been able to successfully pass the exam the first time longer to study the basic language course.
