Employees of fast food restaurants and supermarkets in the U.S. are on strike.
Up to a quarter of American teens find their first jobs as cashiers at "McDonald's"
In recent days, a wave of anti-low-wage protests has been initiated in the Walmart corporation’s supermarkets and restaurants in popular fast-food chains, such as “McDonald’s,” “Burger King,” “Taco Bell,” “Wendy’s” and “Kentucky Fried Chicken.”
For now no one dares to assert whether or not this wave will reach the nine points, or if it has destined to lose strength and dawn in its early stages.
The protest actions are supported by the trade unions and a number of left-wing NGOs.
In addition to the increase in modest wages received by Walmart workers and those from the fast food system, the goal of protest organizers is to create workers’ unions in these companies.
For now, this sector of the economy has hardly been occupied by the trade union movement.
Forty-six cents a year?
Stocks began last week, after Thanksgiving, the so-called "Black Friday." That day, in the United States began the orgy of sales that captured millions of inhabitants, and that was sometimes accompanied by clashes.
That day, some Walmart corporation workers, who employ 2.2 million people worldwide, left their jobs and formed protest pickets alongside unions and left-wing activists in the corporation’s stores, whose products target people of modest and moderate income.
Walmart sells everything from diapers, game rifles and car batteries, to vacuum cleaners, eggs and milk.
The products in their stores are on average between 8% and 27% cheaper than those of the largest supermarkets.
That’s why many underpaid Walmart workers buy only at work.
Product availability and assortment have made Walmart one of America’s largest corporations.
According to two critics, Walmart can afford to sell products at a very low price, in part because it pays little to its workers.
The latter also complain about poor working conditions, such as the lack of forklifts or handheld scanners.
That "Black Friday" the participants of the demonstration demanded the increase in wages and complained that the cost of health insurance provided by the corporation went from 30 to 100 dollars per month.
For a typical Walmart worker, who receives 9.5 dollars per hour, this spending is excessive, they said.
Scientists at the University of California, Berkeley argue that if Walmart raises the average wage to $12 per hour, this will cost the corporation 3.2 trillion dollars.
This is about 1.1% more than what you spend on wages now.
If Walmart places the pay raise on consumers’ shoulders, each store visit will be only 46 cents more expensive.
In a year they will spend the ridiculous amount of 12.39 dollars more than they spend now.
Walmart supporters say the protest took place in nine states alone and did not cause any loss to the corporation.
"Black Friday" lasted in its stores from 8 p.m. to midnight the next day and, during that time, Walmart sold around 5000 items per second.
In total, their cash registers made the "Black Friday" almost 100 million transactions.
The company’s representative, Dan Fogelman, said in an interview with the left-wing website Huffington Post, that they left their job “less than five” Walmart employees and that the protest had been nothing more than “another public relations stunt,” organized by the workers’ union.
"Free box!"
The protests continued this week in New York, in which the objectives were not precisely the Walmart department store (which in this progressive city do not appreciate them, and that is why for now there are none), but the "McDonald's" and other cheap restaurants.
McDonald's says it sells billions of portions, and then they don't even grant you sick leave and don't get paid for your honest work!
Jumaane Williams, New York City Council member
Currently, according to federal law and New York law, the minimum wage is $7.25 per hour.
Fast-food restaurants increase over time, but only slightly, and on average, ordinary workers receive 8.90 dollars per hour in New York.
No one earns less than them in this city.
How it is possible to survive in New York with that money, for me it is incomprehensible.
There was a time when nearly a quarter of American teenagers passed through McDonald’s and worked there, behind the counters, part-time after school, though they still lived with their parents.
Few were the ones who saw this as the main source of income or planned to stay there for a long time.
Now, I constantly stumble in some interviews with McDonald’s workers who complain that they have to live on this salary, and sometimes even feed their children.
On the other hand, in a forum in the Wall Street Journal there is a comment whose author points out that it is irresponsible to have children if he does not know what to feed them with.
Participants in the protests, which began at 6:30 a.m. Thursday at McDonald's 40th Street and Madison Avenue, demanded that cashiers and fast-food cooks start paying at least $15 an hour, that is, their current minimum wage.
They also demanded that in the fast food sector, workers’ unions be created.
U.S. law prohibits the administration from preventing this right and punishing labor movement activists with arguments and layoffs.
Moreover, administration rarely makes their lives easier.
But, for objective reasons, it is easy for unions to cover the fast food sector.
One of the main ones is the excessive rotation of the staff.
Discordants
Noisy protests took place that same day at other cheap restaurants in Manhattan.
The culmination of the action took place midway through the McDonald's rally near Times Square, in which several local Democratic politicians, notably City Council member Jumaane Williams, who said: "McDonald's says it's selling billions of portions, and then doesn't even give you a hospital or pay you for your honest work."
The protesters received support from other prominent New York Democrats, for example City Mayor Bill de Blasio, who said "we must support fast food workers to get fair wages and the economic prosperity that every New Yorker deserves."
As the New York Times described it, this has been the biggest such manifestation in American fast food history.
But only a few hundred people participated in it, even not all of them were employees of the fast food service, in which tens of thousands of people from New York work.
It is not yet clear whether this will serve as a spark to provoke a massive movement.
"For now, deceiving the brain is not so easy"
The issue of augmented reality, so popular among fans of modern technologies, is lately perceived mainly through the prism of special glasses.
Earlier in the summer, at its annual conference Google demonstrated a moving model and subsequently, in November, it emerged that Microsoft had also filed an application to claim the corresponding patent.
However, from a conversation with the head of the interactive 3D technology group in the Microsoft laboratory of Cambridge, Izadi Sharamom, it was elucidated that for the scientists of that company, the glasses already belonged to a past stage.
They are attracted by the prospect of manipulating virtual objects in the air with bare hands and creating open virtual spaces.
- Please, in general terms, what is the subject of study of your research group?
- We are dedicated to person-computer interaction, but we also try to push the boundaries of this interaction.
For now humanity in its great mass has been trapped in the working stage with the pixels of the flat screen, sometimes it touches it with the finger.
But we want to look 5-10 years ahead and guess the cardinal changes in this interaction.
For example, the Xbox console and Kinect sensors represent a step forward and today no Xbox is sold without Kinect, since everyone is interested in gesture control.
- What else does the future hold?
- Even though Kinect has taken the interaction to the physical level, much of it still happens on a flat screen, sometimes in 3D.
The input of information has improved (the system receives more data), and the output is still not very good.
We are trying to change this, we work on truly three-dimensional visualization systems, based on different technologies, including design.
The world must be freed from our computer science, the physical, make it more tangible.
For this, however, it is necessary to recognize not only the user, but also the space around him.
Then we can complete the real world with virtual objects in a more comfortable way.
First of all, the hell with those silly virtual reality headsets!
- What do you think about voice control?
A very popular detail, but don't you think they overestimate it?
- Of course you can not be considered a panacea, you are waiting to resolve the question of privacy, since you do not always want others to know about our actions and intentions.
In fact, all types of computer interaction are good, but each in their own field.
For example, for device control in public places, we had a project where we thought about gestures, but not in loose movements, but shorter.
In addition, the gestures were captured not by the camera of the device, but by a bracelet that recorded the movement of bones and muscles.
For now it is very large, but in theory it can be reduced to the size of a wristwatch.
But, in general, the future is for a combined type of control, for example gesture + voice.
- How's that?
- For example, how would you ask me to pass this can of soda to you?
You will talk and show it at the same time.
- I usually just talk.
- Oh, that's gonna be really hard to recognize.
- I mean, you want to force users to adapt to what the machine can or cannot do at this time?
- Not necessarily, but it's a mutual approach.
I think that in the near future we will have to work mainly on the design of new types of sensors that can accurately determine the reactions of the person.
These can be, for example, laser sensors, as they provide good depth resolution, which is very important.
- If we talk about your work with Xbox Kinect sensors, what are your complaints about modern cameras?
Are you lacking in resolution, depth or something else?
In principle, the current generation is what may be the beginning of our work with three-dimensional recognition.
Of course, it would be good to get 8 megapixels at the speed of 1000 fps.
But the question is not in the megapixels, but in the quality of the matrix and in the depth.
From this last point of view, all current technologies are not good enough for us; this gives more work to algorithm designers.
That is, we have to remember not only the resolution on the X and Y axes, but also in Z.
Also important is the speed, the number of frames per second.
Human movements are quite dynamic and the current 30 fps are really scarce, especially for gestures.
Steven Bathiche, from our lab in Redmond, made a contact sensor with adjustable processing delay from 1 to 100 ms and it is worth mentioning that the modern sensors produced in series are closer to the second value (60-100).
Not everyone understands to what extent this affects the human-machine interaction.
I would be very useful for my work an equivalent of such a device, but that does not require contact for the frames per second to be more.
- And you don't need to increase the number of cameras?
- The Kinect now has three "cameras", one of which is in fact the infrared emitter and the second is the receiver of the reflected signal.
But the third camera is actually a simple visible tuning fork sensor.
This is not used to determine the depth of the object.
Potentially, more cameras could solve the problem...
Or on the contrary, increase it and increase the required amount of calculations.
It would be nice to create a flexible Kinect analog, play with the location curvature of the cameras and see how this would help determine the three-dimensional position.
- From what I remember, Microsoft, unlike Google, has not presented its glasses to the public.
Doesn’t it seem to you that, from the standpoint of everyday use of augmented reality technologies, glasses are one of the most visible platforms?
- Of course, spending all your time holding a smartphone up in your hands, it is not very comfortable, but I think: the best option would be a "transmutable" augmented reality when, based on a cloud platform, you could move from glasses to smartphone,
Glasses are very personal devices, that is what your strength is in (private things only you can see them), but also your weakness: an augmented reality based on glasses will not allow you to work on virtual objects together with other people.
- Let's imagine for a moment that the manipulation of virtual holographic objects in the air is available not only to Tony Stark from the movie "Iron Man", but also to any simple mortal.
There is a problem in this idea that critics often point out: there is no tactile answer!
The hands don't feel anything!
What answers does your group prepare for this challenge?
- In my lectures I often say that augmented reality is the seventh irruption in the interaction between man and machine.
I think the octave might well be the addition of tactile sensations.
Meanwhile, one of the most interesting tricks is the use of the second hand in support quality for the image.
Record the touch perfectly!
But there are also technologies that are truly geared towards bringing tangibility to these “images in the air.” For example, the interference of several ultrasonic rays directed at a specific point where the finger is located gives a feeling similar to what one feels if someone was blowing it into the fingertips, but that feeling is still very weak.
There are also wrist bracelets that influence the nerve endings of the fingers, this also a promising direction.
- Have you tried to fool the brain?
Make you think he feels what it looks like he should feel the moment he sees something?
- That's a good idea, we haven't tried yet.
Here is another challenge that we will have to fight for a long time, how to make a person physically located in a very small space thinks that he goes to an open space, almost endless. We are also working on the idea of treadmills (not like gyms), mobile platforms, as well as that of giant balloons.
For now, deceiving the brain is not so easy, you still have to work for many years.
That is what makes the work with virtual reality attractive to researchers, which many things are in a state of total conception.
