Giving birth in space
The Earth is in danger.
Global warming or collision with a killer asteroid.
Spacecraft caravans with humans on board leave in search of a spare planet.
To preserve humanity, the main question is asked: How to continue the species in conditions of weightlessness or on the same spare planet?
I think there's little to choose from.
In fact, only two are true planets that can be colonized, at least hypothetically.
“These are Venus and Mars,” says the head researcher at the State Astronomical Institute, Sternberg P.K. (IAES), Vladimir Surdin.
But if conditions on Mars are better for life, on the surface of Venus the temperature is 500 degrees.
You can only live at high altitudes or in the orbit of Venus... in space.
We began to address reproductive problems in space with flora.
Experiments with plants have been carried out for half a century.
Four generations of peas grown in orbit were not different in any terrestrial varieties.
Then came the breeding of insects in the orbit, small fruit flies, the drosophilics.
In 1979, quail eggs were sent to the space to check how the embryo develops in weightless conditions.
We get a normal chick as a result.
But then the problems begin.
"The problem is that this chick has to find support, it must stay on its own feet and start moving," explains Vladimir Sychev, the director of the laboratory of the Institute of Biomedical Problems (IPBM) of the Russian Academy of Sciences.
Finding no support, the chicks randomly flipped.
And after 10 hours in the newborns there was a total atrophy of the instincts.
The chicks did not react to light or sound.
And the misfortune was that after four days they simply died.
"And twice we got the chicks to be born, but then we left it because it was impossible to work there with them," says Vladimir Sychev of the experiment with the chicks in space.
The last time a biological "miniarch" flew into orbit was 16 years ago.
Experiments will continue in the spring of 2013.
However, only same-sex species will travel in the biosatellite "Bion".
There was an experiment with rats, which were sent into space already with fetuses.
In principle, nothing supernatural was found.
"This was precisely in biosatellites, but this was a unique experiment, and studies like this must be carried out," says Vladimir Sychev.
After landing, the space rats had offspring.
However, the problem of reproduction directly in space has not yet been addressed.
