Is it an office similar to our NKU or is it organized differently?
As for the offices, like the NKÚ, there acts the Bundesrechnungshof (Federal Court of Accounts), with an organization similar to ours, with a school as well, the only thing is that in its case it is structured somewhat differently, but in principle both offices evolve in parallel.
Also the competencies are to some extent analogous, however, while Germany has a federal organization, the courts of accounts are even at this level. In this respect it differs slightly from our system.
The Federal Court of Auditors (BRH) can only control federal money, which we call state funds here.
Public funds, which are administered by regions and municipalities, there, in Germany, are controlled in the Federal Court of Auditors.
As for local legislation, is it simpler than ours?
I would not usually like to draw a comparison without concrete data. However, Germany remains a model in some respects, but it cannot be pinpointed exactly where it is better.
Could it be better, for example, in terms of the quality of the inspectors?
That's sure not, but, I repeat, I don't like to make this kind of comparison.
It must be said that even those countries we take as a model must face a large number of problems.
If it were not so, it would not be any benefit to collaborate with our office, do you think?
As for the legislation of our country, what did the amendment of the law on public awards mean for your Office? Is their incidence manifested in any way?
Given that the period of validity of this amendment is relatively short, it has not yet been manifested in the control proceedings.
Since we perform ex-post checks, some delay is required.
For now, it is observed in the process of preparing future controls: we have started a new tool of "detection of non-economic risks", through which we have passed almost 14,000 public awards, which have been analyzed. The changes will be perfectly reflected here, since the limits are modified, the conditions of some types of the selection process are rectified and the like.
Do you think that the passage of this law is beneficial or that, rather, it is a mess for the bureaucratic system?
I think this law is surely a step in the right direction and I hope so.
The problem that may arise is that the regulation "hardens" and that it is impossible to comply with it.
Already with the previous regulations, controlled persons were linked to the contractor (e.g. in the case of regional operational programmes of the regional council), and each unrespected law on public procurement meant violation of budgetary discipline.
Does it make sense to tighten the law in this way?
I think not this way.
The system must exclude those who want to attack or take advantage of it and not punish those who make a formal failure, which has no impact on decision-making.
Such a system will only create greater bureaucratic pressure.
And how do you get out of this?
We will see where this initiated path leads us.
The prime minister has recently stated that the SDG would not disturb businessmen with controls of the so-called švarc system, with reference to being autonomous only on paper. What does this mean?
Is the švarc system prohibited or permitted?
The law must be regulated in some way and, if prohibited, then not even the prime minister of government can prevent the action of the Office that has the obligation to carry out such checks and demand obligations.
You can say, "We change the law and we allow it," but it can't say we'll do like we're doing anything.
In the law on public procurement, the regulations are quite strict as to how formally action should be taken. This is how it should be to protect public competition.
But, on the other hand, it is tragic that the candidate is excluded with the best offer for not meeting the formal demands.
The law will never be perfect, but its application must be correct. This is, in my opinion, what we lack.
