Poland and the cosmos.
At the meeting of European Space Agency country ministers held last week, Poland was accepted as a twelfth ESA member. It is the second ESA member of the former Eastern European bloc, after the Czech Republic, which became a full member on 12 November 2008).
Poland initiated intensive collaboration with ESA in 1994 and during the following years participated in the agency’s project commission.
However, Poland’s path to the cosmos began much earlier.
Polish enthusiasts were already engaged in space flights before World War II, although their work was not always understood.
I remember, for example, the A conference. Šternfeld at the Warsaw Astronomical Observatory in which, on December 6, 1933, he presented his ideas on the pioneering study "Introduction to Cosmonautics".
The ideas of the young engineer (born 1905) left the attendees indifferent and, years later, Šternfeld recalled that Dr. Jan Gadomski had been the only one who had shown interest in his work.
In 1934 Šternfeld won the Robert Esnault-Pelterie and André Louis Hirsch Prize in France for his "Introduction to Cosmonautics".
Dr. Jan Gadomski (1899 - 1966), mentioned above, later became a great driver of astronomy and cosmonautics.
He published hundreds of articles in Polish magazines and wrote a series of books devoted to this scientific discipline.
Gadomski became a promoter of cosmonautics, was known all over the world and his contribution to science was rewarded when he named himself to one of the craters on the far side of the moon.
Already in 1925 a dresin was built in Poland that was to be provided with a rocket engine.
Unfortunately, it is unknown who was the author of the proposal and the details of the project are not known.
It is not clear whether the rocket would be used for the start of the dresin or for braking.
The information about this dresin is limited to the one collected in the press of the time.
From 1933 the Polish artillery began to devote itself to missiles.
The research was funded by the Komórka Techniki Uzbrojenia in collaboration with Prof. Mieczyslawem Wolfkem and prof. Gustawem Mokrzyckiegim.
From the preserved material, it becomes clear that the investigation reached the stage of the practical tests.
However, with the arrival of German troops, the investigation was interrupted.
In 1937 the prototype of a photoelectric hunting missile designed by the engineer Rohoziński appeared in the specialized press and the following year the study "Rakieta - torpedo powietrzna and rakietobomba lotnicza", by the author Leliwa-Krzywoblocki, was published.
Both projects were intended for military use of missile engines.
Shortly before the war, the Interim Scientific Advisory Committee (Tymczasowy Komitet Doradczo-Naukowy) was responsible for all missile techniques projects for military use and coordinated all work.
The committee was founded in 1937, but after two years of activity, it was interrupted by the start of the war.
Other studies devoted to cosmonautics appeared in the Polish press after the war thanks to the work of the Polish Astronautical Society (Polskie Towarzystwo Astronautyczne).
In the November 1954 issue of the magazine Problemy, reference is made for the first time to society with four very extensive articles dedicated to astronautics.
In one of them, from the teacher. M. Subotowicze, it was proposed the creation of a society that would be dedicated to cosmonautics.
At that time, artificial satellite projects had already been launched and it was obvious that cosmic research was a discipline with future prospects.
Since the beginning of 1956 the Polish Society of Astronautics (PTA) aspired to be part of the International Federation of Astronautics (founded in 1951) and in the autumn of that same year the PTA became a full member.
The following year the first president of the PTA, Kazimierz Zarankiewicz (1902 - 1959), became the vice president of the International Federation of Astronautics.
He served this position until his death in 1959.
Beginning in 1956, the PTA participated significantly in the development of the RM (Rakieta Meteorologiczna) probe rocket, which was a success and became the first Polish rocket to conduct scientific research.
The first type RM-1 was completed in 1957 and was first released on October 10, 1958.
The rocket had a heyday of 1,800 meters, about 80 cm in length and did not reach 5 kg in weight.
Later, the RM-1A version was completed and in the summer of 1959 aerial tests of the two-stage RM-2 rockets began in the Błędów desert.
The rocket measured 1.4 meters and weighed about 11.5 kg.
Another type of rocket in development was to be the subject of real scientific study. The RM-34 rocket was to have a heyday of 14.5 km and its mission would be to control the high wind.
In 1962, however, work was suspended.
The successor to the first RM-type rockets was the Meteor-1 rocket, which was built during 1962 and 1965.
It was designed as a two-stage rocket, with a total length of 510 cm and an initial weight of 32.5 kg.
Three types (called Meteor-1A, -1B and -1C) were developed, which differed from each other by the space available for scientific devices.
In the Meteor-1A rocket, the space available for volume was 0.4 liters, in the Meteor-1B 0.34 liters and in the Meteor-1C of 0.62 liters.
The maximum heyday in the three types was 37 km.
Between 1965 and 1968 the Meteor-2 rocket was developed at the Air Institute, whose first aerial tests began in October 1970.
The Meteor-2 rocket had an initial weight of 380 kg and was capable of carrying a useful weight of 10 kg up to 60 km high.
Subsequently, the Meteor-2H and Meteor-3 version were built.
It is also necessary to mention the entry of Poland into the COSPAR (Committee for Space Research) in 1960 and the formation of the national committee of COSPAR two years later.
Under the Interkosmos program, Poland joined the research of the cosmic space on Soviet artificial satellites and, in 1978, the Polish pilot Miroslaw Hermaszewski became the second intercosmonaut after Vladimir Remek.
The suspension of the law on social work is not the solution.
Last week the constitutional court suspended the law working social work.
The resolution sparked a heated discussion in society.
It will certainly be interesting to examine the existing problem from a broader point of view.
Liberal economic systems in the EU, as in the globalised world, are based on the principle of greater economic and less normative competition.
Consequently, this means that different economic forms and national economic systems are in permanent conflict with each other.
The cause lies in the principle of free trade and the free and unlimited movement of private capital, along with rampant financial speculation.
The effect of large differences in the labor cost (of wages) produces economic tensions.
Under this concept it is necessary to understand the situation in which the manufacturer, with the import of cheap goods, tries to shorten distances and for this "provokes a decrease" of the price of the competitor in order to take most of the market and, thus, increase its profit margin.
On a large scale it means, for most entrepreneurs, moving production abroad, buying cheaper there or disappearing. The result is high unemployment in those countries where the price of labour, compared to other economies, is higher.
Because private capital has no social responsibility and, with it, it is not responsible for the unemployment that this phenomenon generates, the social expenditure of the state necessarily grows.
This whole situation promotes the total disinterest of entrepreneurs for paying taxes and compensating for the economic and social damages they have caused in their desire to obtain profits.
The situation is universally so well known that there is no need to submit specific statistical data.
The unscrupulous practices of private capital create situations, in certain economies, in which the governments of those countries are forced to compete with the aim of artificially reducing the social level of the population itself and thus attracting foreign capital to the country.
In other words, governments make private capital available to their own population without regard to social decline.
This is especially evident in the changes of the laws in force.
The aim is to force the population to accept the dictation of private capital, especially with regard to wages.
This takes place, on the one hand, through the system of economic obligation in the case of long-term unemployment; on the other, through the restricted right of employees in terms of labour rights.
The result is increasing poverty along with the increasing differences between poor and rich.
For a number of years now, there have been food delivery points in Germany for poor people who cannot be sustained by their own work.
The number of people receiving this type of help already reaches a million.
Within the framework of the increase in the competitiveness of the German economy, there is a fairly frequent case: people employed with such a low salary that the state must pay the rest to reach the minimum essential to survive.
Such a scandal was made public related to the situation of the auxiliary employees of the German federal parliament.
Savings measures from virtually every southern EU state lead, without a doubt, to the same situation. People, pressured by an abysmal decline in their social level, are forced to emigrate like in the 19th century or to survive with a lousy wage at the edge of society, hoping that one day private investment capital will arrive in the country.
Do you need to ask yourself where it comes from?
In the event that it is other EU countries, then poverty passes from one country to another or never comes, since Chinese, Indians, Brazilians, Turks, Moroccans, Egyptians or Africans continue to work for a tiny part of a European salary.
This also affects all of Latin America.
Liberal theories and the media affirm to satiety that the state should not contribute capital to the economy, which directing the economy leads to its failure.
Private capital defends tooth and nail the thesis that the state should not intervene in the economy by intruding on control.
Next, it is necessary to ask whether private capital does not influence its egoism in political march and, therefore, throughout the state.
In this case the answer is clearly affirmative.
The proof is the existence of lobbies, in practice very powerful and omnipresent, in all states.
The result is a desperate situation that manifests itself in the field of corruption, in mutual favours, in legislation that is practically reprehensible everywhere but is not punishable.
In Germany the situation is this: state ministries, in the absence of financial means, commission the drafting of bills to private legal companies, which are often linked to industry.
These types of bills are then passed in the Bundestag, the German parliament.
Thus, all power does not emanate from the people, as announced in the constitutions of Western democracies, but from the strong financial groups that represent their own interests.
It is obvious that democracies with a liberal orientation are quickly in a situation as the one described by Appiános in his work The crisis of the Roman republic in the time of Caesar and Pompeii: "The state had long been disintegrating and the administrations were forcibly occupied."
In exchange for bribes, favors obtained illegitimately and help to finance stones or swords.
Bribery and corruption spread unhindered and people went to the polls with the vote spoken out in advance" ... "there were no people with character who aspired to a position in the administration, so once, because of this disorganization, the state was eight months without consuls" ... "He began to be serious that the only remedy for such a serious situation was autocracy and that it was necessary to choose an energetic man." Although Appiános thought of Pompeii, Caesar rose to power and transformed democracy forever into autocracy.
The conclusion, just as in seniority, is that today’s society is based on inconsiderate preferences of individual profit without regard to common interests.
Private capital is not able, in its essence, to understand and claim the benefits of the whole society.
The result is the same as that of the time, an unprecedented decline of the elite, without an effort to reform it in depth.
The causes of the rise of fascist and communist regimes must therefore be sought in the unbridled liberalization of economic systems in the 19th and 20th centuries.
With respect to the current situation, it is possible to consider the disappearance of these systems for the benefit of a liberal democracy, as a definite pause, pending the next coup.
The really demolishing fact is that the current elite completely ignore the losses of hundreds of thousands in lives, social and humanitarian catastrophes that we have witnessed, as well as the crimes against humanity, as we know them in ancient and most recent history.
The suspension of the public procurement law is not the solution; at least not in the long term.
Under pressure from economic competition, both internationally and within the EU, the government of the Czech Republic will be forced to continue to seek other avenues to reduce the social level of the population.
This trend is therefore systemic.
The solution is through concrete socio-political reforms, which reinforce both the participation of state capital and the influence of citizens in the government and weaken the monopoly position of private capital in society for the benefit of the state.
