Movie Argo: If it gets raw, call Hollywood
In November 1979 a group of the Islamist student demonstration occupied the American embassy in Tehran and took 52 graduates hostage.
His release was to be in exchange for the dethroned Shah Mohamed Réza Páhlevi, who after the revolution fled to the U.S., a country that had sponsored his regime for decades.
For the American administration the situation offered no positive outlook: throwing the shah overboard could not afford it, since, if it did, it endangered the confidence of its allies in other countries.
But the release of the hostages in Iran, where the revolution had led to the constitution of the theocratic regime, was not within its reach.
It was a blow to the prestige of the United States, which subsequently further intensified with the failed attempt to release the hostages by force.
The imprisoned diplomats were released 444 days after the Algerian government’s negotiating intervention.
In the U.S., his fate caused a wave of solidarity and animosity against Iran.
The failure in Iran contributed decisively to the defeat of Jimmy Carter against Ronald Reagan in the 1980 presidential election.
Director and actor Ben Affleck's film "Argo" tracks an episode of this story, which garnered a small hit for America.
Shortly before occupying the embassy, six employees escaped from the building.
After a complicated journey, they ended up in the Canadian embassy residence.
CIA, in collaboration with Canadian authorities, managed to get them out of Iran, for this a covert story helped an extravagant point: they came out with Canadian passports, as members of the film team that examined the location in the country for the filming of a science fiction blockbuster.
Combination of genres
The plan drawn up by "exfiltration" expert Toni Mendez required Hollywood collaboration.
For the lie to seem truthful, it was written about the film project in specialized magazines, press conferences were organized, the fictional production society even had a real office.
Details about the operation were kept secret for a long time, the film has been made from Tony Mendez’s memories.
The Affleck film is a unique combination of various genres.
On the one hand, a realistic political thriller; on the other, a so-called "caper movie", the story of an episode that went well, a hoax (an example may be the Ocean's Eleven series).
In the film, moods are combined. We found well-documented sequences from Tehran on the one hand. In the sequence of credits, emblematic photographs of the time of events are shown, which were captured in the same way in the film; there are not many differences in this regard.
On the other, typical Hollywood scenes somewhat lighter, marked by irony and a slight exaggeration.
And in addition, scenes from the CIA headquarters and other institutions: sucked men who analyze the situation at the negotiating table, in the halls of the office, by phone...
Ben Affleck has managed to restart his career in an excellent way.
The actor, who had been mocked, has become a respectable director and his way of acting has ceased to be the target of ironic comments.
Argo is his third feature film, after "Goodbye, Goodbye" (2007) and the thriller "The Town. City of Thieves" (2010).
At the same time, it is the first Affleck film in which the action has no place in the city of Boston, where it was raised.
Likewise, the sensitivity of capturing the atmosphere of the place was a feature that placed the directors of old films above Hollywood standards.
And Affleck proves it in Argo, where Tehran "wheels" in Canada.
The best scenes of the film take place in the streets, in the reconstruction of the true events. The introductory sequence of the seizure of the embassy is impressive for its synoptic capacity that, at the same time, conveys the emotion of bewilderment and the lack of foresight that arises when, somewhere, history takes a step forward.
Affleck and his collaborators achieve a similar effect on fictional scenes (the impostor team at Tehran bazaar).
Too much action in too many places
The director had to accept the fact that an explained story does not offer much in the cinematic sense of the most intriguing scenes.
And he manages pretty well. Sometimes he adds something to reality: here everything does not come out so elegantly (the scene in which the crisis lurks in the airport in Tehran, the deviation of a call to America and the unbridled search behind its runway become crazy).
Argo’s weakness is the lack of control that arises from the need to show too much action in too many places.
Alan Arkin and John Goodman have a very funny role as Hollywood collaborators, although their characters deserved more space and are not, by far, the only ones in this film.
For these reasons, the Affleck film loses a little dramatic stroke, but it is a film that can be followed with a moderate interest, value its realization and the retro style of a thriller that evokes the 70's.
But let it collapse, that will be difficult.
As an evocation of a true story and as proof of how exaggerated the notions of omnipresence and omniscience of the secret services may be, is sufficient.
