The architecture studio MVRDV demonstrates that the real adventures are not only in the head – in the example of the Spijkenisse library and the newly finished “montain of books” – 2 photos
“I think the building is fun, it looks futuristic, and there’s finally something interesting to see,” says Lisette Verhaig, a passerby passing through the street.
And Stefan Spermon, IT technician at a large company located near the library, points out: "In addition, the building is beautiful."
But I wonder why we need a library today.
We all have internet, tablets and e-books.
No one comes in for pleasure in those old-fashioned libraries, right?
Spijkenisse, a dormitory city located at the gates of Rotterdam that is barely worth a fleeting visit, holds the dubious honor of having risen with a record to forget.
The population of 80,000 has the lowest literacy rate in the Netherlands.
To counter this shameful situation, some years ago it was decided to contribute in some way to the general culture and copy the seven fictional bridges that appear represented in the euro banknotes in the form of decorated reinforced concrete miniatures.
The success of the educational offensive was limited.
And that’s how policymakers decided that there was only one possibility to improve the statistics: a library had to be built!
Winy Maas, from the Dutch architecture studio MVRDV, a master in the art of bar diagrams and responsible for fun buildings while cynical, took the subject with his usual serenity and appeared to the presentation of the contest in 2003 with five books under his arm and a smile on his face.
And while the jury looked perplexed around him and shrugged, Maas proceeded to stack the books by size forming a pyramid and concluded his brief speech with the following words: "Dear fellow citizens:
Here you have it, my proposal for the mountain of books of Spijkenisse, the so-called `Boekenberg'."
Nine years later, the mountain of 30 million euros rises at the planned place.
This is part of the revitalization project, which is completed with an underground parking, a supermarket, a post office and a couple of residential and townhouse buildings.
In early November the mountain of books was awarded the second prize "Best Library of NL 2012".
In addition, the project is also nominated for the 2012 "Dutch National Wood Award".
In this way, the small town lacking in history, which to date had nothing more to offer than a postmodern pedestrian area and an incredibly ugly town hall behind whose white facade one would rather intuit a dairy plant, now has a work of contemporary architecture.
But above all, Spijkenisse now has the first public cultural building in its history.
The Long Way to the Book
The first impression is that it is a book paradise under a cheese maker.
It is true that there is an elevator that transports us right to the center of this mountainous massif, but the real lovers of space and reading do not use it, but prefer to merge with their topography at every step of their climbing to the top.
The fully glazed interior is bright and easy to cover with the view, the annealed brick floor and elegant streetlights unequivocally support the public condition of the library.
The urban environment is perfect.
When you look up you can get to visualize the park benches, dogs and children playing football.
And everywhere books, books and more books.
“Normally book shelves are arranged along the facade and in the center opens a huge dark room that is usually somewhat uncomfortable and impersonal,” says Winy Maas.
What we have done is turn the classic spatial configuration upside down and take the reading area from the inside to the outside.
The interior of the mountain is very well used: in the middle are the offices, the Internet library, the chess club, the environmental education center and the maintenance room.
Special mention deserves the black shelves that assume the functions of mural cladding, parapet and railing at the same time.
The sight, touch and smell are strange.
Even the most everyday architects and civil engineers shake their heads when they hear about this unknown material.
“We wanted to work with recycled materials,” Joop Trouborst, project manager in the city of Spijkenisse, told us.
And that’s how one day, in a Frisian farm, we come across the right by-product from agriculture.
For many years, a plastic fabric of few millimeters thick has been used in greenhouses and in the fields of the Netherlands as a basis for holding crop roots.
It is a cheap and efficient material.
This thin fabric lasts two seasons and is then discarded.
For the library this fabric was pressed, for the first time in such quantities, to get plates four centimeters thick.
With heat and pressure, the so-called agricultural plastic (KLP) changes color and becomes a dark, homogeneous and resistant material that smells like a new car mix and sneaker.
After 105 steps you reach the top of the mountain.
At the end of this continuous route of almost 500 meters around the mountain awaits us the reward: from the cafeteria you not only have a fantastic view of the city, but in it you can also enjoy some tasty Dutch croquettes and their ficus planted in huge pots.
These create a pleasant atmosphere while maintaining the right atmospheric humidity for this mountain of literature.
Donations for a new soul
"Even if it is difficult to believe given its large glazed surfaces, this building is an exemplary project when it comes to ecology," says Trouborst.
The necessary heating and cooling are obtained from geothermal energy.
Although the mountain of books is situated under a huge glass pyramid, even on the sunniest days the sun only shines for a few hours inside.
The huge wooden trusses located transverse to the glass facade serve to shade and absorb most of the sun’s rays.
This creates a comfortable indoor climate.
The rest is an automatic blind.
Stefan Spermon, the skeptical worker in the Information Technology sector, has already dared to step foot in the new library.
And Lisette Verhaig has also been there.
Traditional Chinese medicine teacher Cynthia Bogarde has also visited the library. She calls Spijkenisse's "Boekenberg" the "late soul."
The reason is that, on the occasion of the inauguration that took place a couple of weeks ago, all the inhabitants of the city were invited to donate a book from their private collection.
In this way it is intended to fill, for the moment, the optical gaps of a library that does not yet have its complete archive; at present it has 70,000 copies.
The concept has gone deep.
The shelves are packed.
“There’s nothing worse than a half-empty library,” says architect Winy Maas.
"I think that thanks to our initiative now all the inhabitants have a certain link with this building.
Everyone knows that his book is part of the library.
Even if it's just there to adorn.
In this way, the MVRDV study has achieved a success in that discipline that reigns that in specialized slang it is known as "creation of an identity".
The city of Spikhenisse has written a piece of the history of literature.
Regardless of how young and unfinished it may be.
Finally a starting point to shape your identity.
