"Mark protection" in China: when Puma and Armani suddenly become Chinese brands
Armani is a well-known brand worldwide and Polo Ralph Lauren is also.
What is Armani Polo?
Behind this name hides a denomination officially registered in China but that has nothing to do with the original companies.
However, it enjoys protection while the real eponyms do not file a lawsuit.
And even then it is not clear that they will be right.
“It’s increasingly difficult for foreigners to protect their trademarks in China,” said Thomas Pattloch, a lawyer at the law firm Taylor Wessing specializing in protection rights violations in the Far East.
Every week a new case arrives at my table.
Imitators simply add a couple of letters to be able to register their trademarks.
In this way, Gucci becomes Lu-Gucci and instead of Prada Prada-Kny is registered.
German companies are also legally copied in the same way, as has happened to the sports goods manufacturer Puma.
Pattloch opens a file cabinet in which it stores seats in the Beijing brand office.
On 14 September 2010 a Chinese company applied to register the Zegna DF Puma brand, an artificial name that was also used by the fashion house Ermenegildo Zegna.
That the Chinese are world champions in copying and violating intellectual property rights is well known.
In large cities there are department stores of several floors dedicated exclusively to the sale of counterfeits.
However, Pattloch cases are of another nature. On behalf of his clients, he fights against the fact that the trademark office officially grants Chinese companies the right to take advantage of a denomination that is already registered elsewhere.
The Chinese call it "Bang Ming Pai" or accompanying brand.
The word has its origin in the Chinese term "Bang Dakuan",
which refers to women who have "fished" a rich man.
Chinese authorities do not feel guilty
"It's harmful to the business, we have to fight it," Pattloch demands.
"The mark makes water, the monopolistic position disappears and the damage that the image suffers is enormous."
The financial losses and procedural costs of the affected sectors are millionaire, especially in the case of emblematic luxury products.
According to data from the market analysis company CLSA, with a volume of 15,000 million euros a year China is, in size, the third market for luxury goods and the one that grows at the fastest pace.
However, achieving the cancellation of registrations of doubtful legality in the registration of trademarks is complicated and also involves a lot of money.
The processes can be prolonged up to nine years and the result is uncertain.
Pattloch talks about cases in which the court dismissed a lawsuit because so much time had elapsed that the name subject to the lawsuit had already become a "market reality."
"If the plaintiff is unlucky, he may even have to pay money to the plagiarist because the process has damaged his brand in China," Pattloch said.
Sometimes this is the law of the jungle.
Some of the most well-known cases have to do with graphic elements.
In 2009 Daimler-Benz lost a lawsuit against construction machinery manufacturer Sany, the company that has recently been absorbed by German concrete pump manufacturer Putzmeister.
That is why today the Chinese can continue to use an emblem very similar to the Mercedes star.
Volvo buyer Geely was initially using a white and blue logo that was largely reminiscent of BMW; the matter was settled in court and Geely had to modify it.
Clothing maker Lacoste lost in China to imitators from Hong Kong and Singapore whose logo represented a crocodile looking in the opposite direction from the original.
The Chinese authorities do not feel guilty.
The CTMO brand office in Beijing recognizes that in 2010 they have had difficulties due to the shortage of equipment and staffing.
Last year, however, "the labor emergency situation returned to normal."
In this way, the number of unprocessed claim processes has been reduced by 22%.
Nearly 57,000 of these cases were resolved, 75% more than the previous year.
However, 81,500 claims remain pending resolution.
Fighting this costs a lot of money
As is usual in China, the figures are surprising.
Last year, the CTMO registered more than 1.4 million trademark protection applications, almost a third more than in 2010.
It would be a new record and means that China leads the list of new registrations worldwide for the 10th consecutive year, according to the brand office.
It seems that this also happens with the number of valid logos, a figure that amounts to 5.5 million in total.
In 2011, 1.8 billion yuan would have been pocketed in rights.
In other words, this means that on average each registration costs 1,280 yuan or 160 euros.
Fighting this costs a lot of money, as evidenced by the case of the German family business Freudenberg.
For more than seven years the group has been fighting in court against a Chinese imitator.
While the Germans have managed to stop the illegal manufacture of imitation car parts,
the imitator has managed to secure Chinese rights over the Freudenberg brand.
"We ourselves have provoked this situation because in Germany the surnames are not protected," says Hanno Wentzler, President and CEO of Freudenberg Chemical Specialities in Munich.
The CTMO trademark office also dismissed the appeal of the Muniquoise.
In the following two instances Freudenberg has been right, but the opposite side is still fighting today.
You have to be very careful
Now the case has reached the doors of the High Court of Justice, where it is still pending resolution.
Wentzler is confident that he will be able to resolve the issue favorably and praises the professionalism of the courts.
However, he also states that “the procedure is extremely expensive, both in terms of money and time.”
It is difficult to estimate internal costs; the business archive has had to review files of up to one hundred years old in order to provide evidence.
Five years ago Freudenberg offered the opposing party a "six-figure sum in euros" with the aim of reaching a friendly agreement, but it was unsuccessful.
"This shows how much we care about," Wentzler says.
The dangers lurking in the Far East threaten even to affect Europe,
specifically if the imitators secure the rights to unprotected trademarks there.
Thus, a Chinese manufacturer tried to register in Germany the Freudenberg name for shoes and leather products.
The group has long since left this commercial area, however, it managed to prevent registration.
"You have to be very careful," Wentzler says.
Both he and lawyer Pattloch recommend German companies to be extremely cautious about doing business with China.
It is not enough to rely on international trademark rights law, but what needs to be done is to "also record in China everything that may be susceptible to protection", as Wentzler points out.
Otherwise, the topic can be much more expensive than a simple record.
In fact, in case Freudenberg lost the last round of his particular battle, then he would have to pay the opposing party license rights by his own name, as Wentzler explains.
That or in the segment in question would drive us out of the market.
