Prosecutors tried to prove Friday that Private Bradley Manning, accused of the largest leak of confidential information in U.S. history, missed multiple opportunities to report ill-treatment he now claims he suffered while under military detention.
During the interrogation that the prosecution carried out to Manning in a preview of the trial in Ft. Meade, Maryland, Attorney Commander Ashden Fein said records of weekly visits by officers from the unit Manning received during nine months of detention in Quantico, Virginia, show no complaint about the treatment he was receiving.
