At Friday's hearing, Fein reviewed with Manning the forms officers filled out after visits to Manning during his arrest at Quantico military prison, where he was imprisoned on a maximum detention basis from July 2010 to April 2011.
Officers would have asked Manning questions and noted his answers.
When Fein asked about the forms on Friday, Manning acknowledged that he had called the treatment given to him by the guards as "excellent" and the treatment received at the facility in general as "very professional".
The forms show no report of ill-treatment, even though officers asked Manning directly about the treatment he received, Fein said.
Manning replied that he had expressed concern about some issues and that the officers who visited him had discussed these problems and had indicated that they would be addressed, but that they did not record those issues in the register.
"They wrote 'no incidents' (after talking about the problems) but this doesn't necessarily mean that I wouldn't have mentioned any problems," Manning said.
Army Colonel Denise Lind also asked Manning why she had not reported the treatment she received during the January 2011 meeting with a council tasked with examining the suicide intentions she had expressed on a form months earlier.
Manning responded that his intention during that meeting was to obtain the reduction of the "injury prevention" regimen under which he was.
The military said it had placed him under that restrictive regime, which is one degree below that of surveillance for possible suicide, to ensure his protection and the safety of other people.
"I wanted the staff to know that I was fine and (I wanted) to stop being under injury prevention ... so I could enjoy what, from my point of view, is a better quality of life," Manning said.
Manning testified Thursday about his arrest in Iraq and his transfer to Kuwait, where he was held for nearly two months before being transferred to the military prison at the Marine Base in Quantico, Virginia, in July 2010.
He said he had considered suicide in Kuwait and that he once lost consciousness due to heat.
He said that the fact that he was not allowed to know what was happening to him or what was happening in the outside world was very distressing.
"My world was reduced only to Camp Arafjon, to that cage," Manning said Thursday.
"I thought I was going to die in that cage."
Manning claimed that, once moved to Quantico, he spent most days in a small cell, at least for 21 hours and often for 23 hours, without company.
Manning said he was only allowed to have a mattress, a blanket, flip-flops, some clothes and his glasses.
He explained that he was trying to move all the time, as it was forbidden to sleep or even lie down during the day.
Manning claimed that he always had a light coming from the outside pointing into his eyes while he was sleeping.
He said that if the guards could not see his face when he turned around at night, they would wake him up to turn around again.
Manning’s lawyer filed a formal claim in January 2011 on the treatment Manning received.
Manning was transferred to Fort Leavenworth Military Prison in Kansas in April 2011.
On Friday, the judge asked Manning about an argument she had made in Thursday’s statement that, after being forced one night to sleep naked in her Quantico cell, she was forced during a morning recount to stand naked in front of guards and other prisoners.
Manning had testified that he had never been given the opportunity to cover himself with the blanket during the count.
During the judge’s interrogation on Friday, Manning said he deduced from the order given to him by the guard who was to drop the blanket he could have covered with, but acknowledged that no one had ordered him to drop it.
Manning testified Thursday that he had been forced to sleep naked the night before because of an attempt to prove to an officer that he posed no danger to himself.
Manning claimed he had told the officer that he could have used the elastic of his underwear or flip-flops to self-harm but that he hadn’t.
Manning testified that that night his underwear, flip-flops and glasses had been removed from his cell.
Her lawyers are hopeful that the judge will at least take into account the experiences she went through during her prison stay and dramatically reduce her sentence should she be convicted on the court-martial, which is scheduled to begin early next year.
