The toughest trade in the world: the human mules of Kawah Ijen
For four euros, the porters of the Indonesian volcano risk life and health by carrying 70 kilos of sulfur through steep stone paths
There are people for whom their work is hell and another who literally work in hell.
This is the case of Anto Wijaya, one of the 400 miners who make a living by taking sulfur from the Kawah Ijen volcano, east of the Indonesian island of Java.
To do this, it has to go down every day to the bottom of its crater, where the sulfurous gas emanating from the bowels of the Earth solidifies when it comes into contact with the air.
After starting large sulfur rocks, which in total weigh about 70 kilos, it carries them in two bamboo baskets that loads on their shoulders through rugged stone paths.
They are only 250 meters to the top of the volcano, which rises to 2,386 meters of altitude, but the exhausted porters take more than 40 minutes to ascend at the passage of a turtle, keeping the balance and sluggishly measuring their steps so as not to slip and fall by the cliff.
They know that any misstep could cost them their lives, as happened to a French tourist who fell for years ago for the cliffs of the Kawah Ijen.
The miners of Kawah Ijen earn 5 euro cents for every kilo of sulfur they extract
Once up, they make their way through the tourists who photograph them as if they were circus monkeys and, fatigoously carrying the heavy baskets, walk three kilometers to the scale that a mining company has placed a little lower, at 1,850 meters high.
This is PT Candi Ngrimbi, a company that exploits the volcano since 1960 and, never better said, to its workers, to which it pays 662 Indonesian rupees (5 euro cents) for every kilo of sulfur.
It then sells it for 10,000 rupees (83 euro cents) to the petrochemical industry, since this mineral is widespread in everyday life and is used to make matches, fireworks, cosmetics, dynamite and even to bleach sugar.
"As usual is to carry 70 kilos, we take out about 46,000 rupees (3.8 euros) on each trip," explains Anto, who usually makes three sizes a day.
It takes three hours in each and ends up ground, but they allow you to gather 138,000 rupees (11.5 euros) at the end of the day.
Although it seems a misery for such inhumane effort, it is three times what it would gain on the field.
"The day of the miners is very high here, where the collection of coffee is paid to 15,000 rupees (1.2 euros) on the day and the average monthly salary is two million rupees (167 euros)", clarifies the carrier, who previously worked as a bricklayer on the tourist island of Bali.
There, his salary was 75,000 rupees (6.2 euros) a day and the pit was not so hard, but Anto has returned with his family to Banyuwangi, a town near the volcano, for a reason of weight that, in Indonesia, is as forceful as sulfur: "I married a young woman from Bali, where they are Hindus, and I have brought her to Java to convert to Islam."
Anto has asthma, breathes with difficulty, coughs constantly and his eyes are irritated by toxic gases
At 27, Anto has been playing his skin for three in the Kawah Ijen, whose sulphur has already begun to take his toll despite covering his face with a mask and special glasses.
He has asthma, breathes with difficulty, coughs constantly and his eyes are irritated by the toxic gases that the volcano fires.
It is the price you must pay to get your dream.
"I will work two more years because I want to open a store or study Spanish or French," he promises in more than acceptable English.
Punished by life, this friendly and intelligent young man could be a tour guide, waiter or hotel receptionist, but instead he does the work of a mule.
Sharing a unclean wooden cabin with other porters, he rises every day at two in the morning because the sulfur does not stop flowing at night, when its characteristic yellow color turns blue and shines in the middle of darkness.
Defiing the shadows, Anto descends into the crater lighting with a small flashlight attached to his helmet, which he himself has bought with his money.
About 400 porters load the sulfur baskets on their shoulders from the bottom of the crater
Despite its penguin benefits, the mining company has not mechanized the extraction of sulfur to save costs or supply any equipment to the carriers, who work on their own and to the extent of the weight.
In fact, they do not even see part of the 30,000 rupees (2.5 euros) of surcharge per camera that, together with the entrance of 15,000 rupees (1.2 euros), the guards of this natural park charge tourists who come to photograph the volcano and its human mules.
“This job is for the beasts and not for the people,” protests Madrusin, a 42-year-old heavy bearer who has been in the Kawah Ijen for three decades, since leaving school.
Able to lift up to 110 kilos, he says that he will endure working "as much as he can" because he needs the money to educate his three children, between 18 and 10 years old.
I won't retire, I'll die here because the volcano has been my whole life
Although sulfur burns the throat and stings the eyes when the wind suddenly changes and traps the miners in the thick columns that come out of the volcano, they are so hard that none complain of serious illness ... beyond, of course, their usual respiratory problems, osteoarthritis, knee pains and sores on the shoulders, which have been malformed by the weight of the baskets.
Swinging the basket on his back, Unainik can only carry 50 kilos at the age of 53.
Every day, he and his companions rip 15 tons of sulfur into the volcano, which three trucks move to the Tamansari warehouse, 18 kilometers away on a goat road between the weeds.
"I will not retire, I will die here because the volcano has been my whole life," Unainik proclaims opening his mouth well, where he is missing several teeth.
Of his five children, the oldest, 30, also works by loading sulfur.
Time passes, but misery perpetuates from generation to generation one of the toughest trades in the world: the one made by the human mules of the Kawah Ijen.
